SUMMARIZER="F">      

Robert Goldwin, a scholar in Constitutional studies at the American
Enterprise Institute doesn't see the Second Amendment as a barrier to
gun control.  Reviewing the debates over the wording of that amendment
in the First Congress, he finds that much of their concern, especially
that of James Madison, was to limit the power of Congress to establish
a standing army and, instead rely on state militias.  One version that
was argued considered the "bearing of arms" as synonymous with "to
render military service" and another would require "every free
able-bodied white male citizen" to enroll in the militia.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d27"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ920211-0036"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="F">        

Richard Goldwin assesses many of the letters he received in response
to his earlier Wall Street Journal column on gun control as
misinterpreting his article and the Second Amendment, and accusing him
of calling for the removal of all guns through regulation, which he
denies.  Goldwin maintains, as does one of his correspondents, that
regulation of gun ownership and use does not violate the constitution.
All letters, Goldwin states, missed his point that gun owners be
required to sign up (not join) with the National Guard.  His main
point was to show how far Congress can go in gun control legislation
without exceeding its Constitutional powers.</SUM>

<SUM
